05/01/22, 15:18 - Aryan Negi: Good afternoon all,
In a meeting convened by Hon'ble VC sir this morning,    the following pointers were discussed:
1. *I semester* theory classes will be conducted in *BLENDED mode* from tomorrow onward. 
2. *I year Students residing in University Hostels* will attend the classes in *PHYSICAL* mode.
3. *I year Students residing as PGs and those that are day scholars*  will have teaching learning conducted in *ONLINE* mode only. 
4. Busses will ply only for Hostel residing Students. 
5. *Ongoing Mid Term practical examinations* for I semester,  shall continue in *PHYSICAL* mode only.

The above mentioned pointers have to disseminated to all concerned stakeholders asap.
Notification regarding the same shall be issued by the competent authority by eod.

int main()
{
	int i,j,N,sum;
	scanf("%d" ,&N);
	for(i=1;i<=N;i++)
	{
		sum=0;
		for(j=1;j<i;j++)
		{
			if(i%j==0)
			{
				sum += j;
			}
		}

		{
			printf("%d ",i);
		}
	}
	return 0;
}

28/01/22, 22:10 - +91 95487 76102: #include <stdio.h>
int main()
{
	int N,x,a,b=1,s=0;
	scanf("%d" ,&N);
	x=N;
	while(N>0)
	{
		a=N%10;
		for(int i=1;i<=a;i++)
		{
			b=b*i;
		}
		s=s+b;
		b=1;
		N=N/10;
	}
	if(s==x)
	printf("Strong Number");
	else
	printf("Not Strong Number");
}

int main()
{
    int i, j, rows;


    scanf("%d", &rows);

    for(i=1; i<=rows; i++)
    {
        for(j=i; j<rows; j++)
        {
            printf(" ");
        }
        for(j=1; j<=(2*i-1); j++)
        {
            if(i==rows || j==1 ||        j==(2*i-1))
            {
                printf("*");
            }
            else
            {
                printf(" ");
            }
        }
        printf("\n");
    }

    return 0;
}

25/02/22, 15:59 - Ayesha: [25/02, 3:46 PM] rawatayesha25: The working of the three-phase induction motor is based on the principle of electromagnetic induction.
When three-phase stator winding of an induction motor is energized from a 3 phase supply, aÂ rotating magnetic fieldÂ is set up which rotates around the stator at synchronous speed (Ns).
This rotating field passes through the air gap and cuts the rotor conductors, which are stationary.
An EMFÂ gets induced in every rotor conductor due to the relative speed between the rotating magnetic flux and the stationary rotor. Since the rotor circuit is short-circuited, currents start flowing in the rotor conductors.
The current-carrying rotor conductors are placed in the magnetic field produced by the stator. Consequently, aÂ mechanical forceÂ acts on the rotor conductors. The sum of the mechanical forces on all the rotor conductors produces aÂ torqueÂ which tends to move the rotor in the same direction as the rotating field.
The fact that the rotor is urged to follow the stator field (i.e., rotor moves in the direction of stator field) can be explained byÂ Lenzâ€™s law.
Now, the cause producing the rotor currents is the relative speed between the rotating field and the stationary rotor conductors.
Hence to reduce this relative speed, the rotor starts running in the same direction as that of the stator field and tries to catch it. This is how a three-phase induction motor starts running.
[25/02, 3:46 PM] rawatayesha25: The rotor conductors are short circuited in a squirrel cage induction motorÂ permits a large magnitude of induced current to flow in the rotor winding or creates a suitable low impedance path for rotor induced current. The induced current generates the magnetic field which is required to rotate the rotor.

07/03/22, 12:29 - +91 70601 30985: #include <stdio.h>
 
void main()
{
    int num1, num2, gcd, lcm, remainder, numerator, denominator;
 
    printf("Enter two numbers\n");
    scanf("%d %d", &num1, &num2);
    if (num1 > num2)
    {
        numerator = num1;
        denominator = num2;
    }
    else
    {
        numerator = num2;
        denominator = num1;
    }
    remainder = numerator % denominator;
    while (remainder != 0)
    {
        numerator   = denominator;
        denominator = remainder;
        remainder   = numerator % denominator;
    }
    gcd = denominator;
    lcm = num1 * num2 / gcd;
    printf("GCD of %d and %d = %d\n", num1, num2, gcd);
    printf("LCM of %d and %d = %d\n", num1, num2, lcm);
}

11/03/22, 09:41 - +91 83683 06343: 1. Which type of language is C?

Ans- C is a high-level language and general purpose structured programming language.

2. What is a compiler?

Ans- Compile is a software program that transfer program developed in a high-level language into executable object code.

3. What is an algorithm?

Ans- The approach or method that is used to solve the problem is called an algorithm.

4. What is a c token and types of c tokens?

Ans- The smallest individual units are known as C tokens. C has six types of tokens Keywords, Constants, Identifiers, Strings, Operators and Special symbols.

5. How many Keywords (reserve word)are in C?

Ans There are 32 Keywords in the C language.

6. What is an identifier?

Ans Identifiers are user-defined names given to variables, functions and arrays.

7. What are the Back Slash character constants or Escape sequence characters available in C?

Ans Back Slash character constant are \t, \n, \0.

8. What is a variable?

Ans- Variables are user-defined names given to memory locations and are used to store values. A variable may have different values at different execution. times during program

9. What are the Data Types present in C?

Ans Primary or Fundamental Data types (int, float, char), Derived Datatypes(arrays, pointers) and User-Defined data types(structures, unions, enum)

10. How to declare a variable?

Ans- The syntax for declaring variable isdata type variable_name-1, 2,....variable_name-n; variable_name

â€¢ Example 1: int a, b;

â€¢ Example 2: float p,q;

11. What is meant by initialization and how do we initialize a variable?

Ans- While declaring a variable assigning value is known as initialization. Variable can be initialized by using assignment operator (=).

12.How many types of operators or there in C?

Ans- C consist Arithmetic Operators (+, -, *, 1,%), Relational Operators (<, <=, >, >=, !=), Logical Operators (&&, II, !), Assignment Operators (, +, -, *=, /=), Increment and Decrement Operators (++,-), Conditional Operator (?:), Bitwise Operators(<<, >>, ~, &â‚ I, ^) and Special Operators (. , >, &, *, size of)

13. What is a Unary operator and what are the unary operators present in C?

Ans- An operator which takes only one operand is called a unary operator. C unary operators are Unary plus (+), Unary minus (-), Increment and Decrement operators (++,-), Address of operator (&), Value at operator (*), sizeof operator, complement operator (~)

14. What is the use of the modulus (%) operator?

Ans- The modulus operator produces the remainder of an integer division. It cannot be used on floating-point data

15. What is the use of printf and scanf functions in C?

Ans-Values of variables and results of expressions can be displayed on the screen using printf functions. Values to variables can be accepted through the keyboard using scanf function

19. What is a loop?

Ans- Loop is a sequence of statements that runs repeatedly.

20. What are loop control statements in C?

Ans- While do-while and for.

*DIFFERENCE BETWEEN THESE*

_The 'for' loop used only when we already knew the number of iterations._

_The 'while' loop used only when the number of iteration are not exactly known._

_In for loop, initialization, condition checking, and increment or decrement of iteration variable is done explicitly in the syntax of a loop only._

_As against, in the while loop we can only initialize and check condition in the syntax of the loop._

_*While loop checks the condition first and then executes the statement(s), whereas do while loop will execute the statement(s) at least once, then the condition is checked. While loop is entry controlled loop whereas do while is exit controlled loop.*_

21. What are sections present in for 
loop?

Ans Initialization section, conditional section and increment/decrement section.

22. What is the use of break
statements?

Ans- The break statement is used to exit from the loop. 

28. What is a function?

Ans- The function is a self-contained block of the statement which is used to perform a certain task

29. What are the types of functions?

Ans- C functions are divided into two categories user-defined function and built-in functions

30. Which are called built-in

functions?

Ans Printf, scanf, clrscr, gotoxy, string handling functions and file handling functions

31. What is a recursive function?

Ans A function calling itself is called function recursion

*Some points to memorize*

1.C language is considered as the mother language of all the modern programming languages because most of the compilers, JVMs, Kernels, etc. are written in C language. 

2. C language is a system programming language because it can be used to do low-level programming (for example driver and kernel)

3. C is considered as a middle-level language because it supports the feature of both low-level and high-level languages. C language program is converted into assembly code, it supports pointer arithmetic (low-level), but it is machine independent (a feature of high-level).

History of C
https://www.javatpoint.com/history-of-c-language

#include is a way of including a standard or user-defined file in the program and is mostly written at the beginning of any C/C++ program. This directive is read by the preprocessor and orders it to insert the content of a user-defined or system header file into the following program.

Header File or Standard files: This is a file which contains C/C++ function declarations and macro definitions to be shared between several source files. Functions like the printf(), scanf(), cout, cin and various other input-output or other standard functions are contained within different header files. So to utilise those functions, the users need to import a few header files which define the required functions.

Greetings Everyone  ğŸ’«ğŸ’«  The wait is over ğŸ‘Œ *IEEE GEHU Student Branch* introduces CODE-CHAOS, 

*CODE-CHAOS* ğŸ’»ğŸ’» is a coding competition open for both 1st and 2nd year of GEHU & GEU (All Courses) ğŸ˜„ğŸ˜„. It provides an excellent opportunity to enhance your coding skills and getting certified by IEEE which can make your resume eye-candy ğŸ­ğŸ­ğŸ¬. 

The competition contains only one phase, a simple coding round which will be conducted on either Hackerearth Or Hackerrank. It will contain 10 MCQ' s and 3 coding questions. You will be given two and a half hours to work on the problem statements. IEEE members will be present in the designated lab to help the participants in their queries.
Venue will be informed two days before the competition. 

All the participants will get a certificate for their participation and the top 3 winners will get exciting prizes ğŸğŸğŸ. *The winner will get prize upto â‚¹1000 ğŸ’¸ğŸ’¸ğŸ’¸ğŸ’¸.*

void sort(int *,int);
int main()
{
int a[100],i,j,n,*p;
p=a;
printf(" enter limit:");
scanf("%d",&n);
printf(" Enter elements of array:");
for(i=0;i<n;i++)
 scanf("%d",p+i);
      display(p,n);
 sort(p,n) ;
 printf(" \n After sort : ");
 display(p,n);
return 0;
}

void display(int *p,int n)
{
   int i; printf(" \n elements of array:");
for(i=0;i<n;i++)
 printf("%d ",*(p+i));

}
void sort(int *p,int n)
{
   int i,j,t;
for(i=0;i<n-1;i++)
{    for(j=0;j<n-i-1;j++)
{ if(*(p+j)>  *(p+j+1) )
   {
t=*(p+j);
*(p+j)=*(p+j+1);
*(p+j+1)=t;
  }

}
}
 
}

*Dear Students,*
The "offline" classes and various activities of the University are conducted between 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM.

26/06/22, 15:23 - Abhishek Joshi: #include <stdio.h>

void sort(int a[], int n)
{
    int *p = a;
    for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
    {
        for(int j=0; j<n-i-1; j++)
        {
            if (*(p+j)>*(p+j+1))
        {
            int t = *(p+j);
            *(p+j) = *(p+j+1);
            *(p+j+1) = t;
        }
        }
    }
}


int main()
{
    int a[100],n;
    int *p;
    p = a;
    printf("enter thhe limit of array: ");
    scanf("%d",&n);
    printf("enter the array: ");
    for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
    {
        scanf("%d",(p+i));
    }
    for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
    {
        printf("\t%d",*(p+i));
    }
    sort(a,n);
    printf("\nthe sorted array is: ");
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
        {
            printf("\t%d",*(p+i));
        }
    return 0;
}

#include <string>
using namespace std;
class student
{

 void input(){
     cout<<"enter the name, roll_no,address\n";
     getline(cin,name);
     cin>>roll_no;
     getline(cin,address);
     }
 
 void display()
 {
    cout<<name<<endl;
    cout<<roll_no<<endl;
    cout<<address<<endl;
    
 }
 };

07/10/22, 12:05 - ayush saklani: ///2/////////////////////////
#include <iostream>
#include<cmath> 
using namespace std;
class triangle{
	public:
	int a;
	int b;
	int c;
	void setdata(){
		cout<<"enter the 3 sides"<<endl;
		cin>>a>>b>>c;
	}
};
int main()
{
	triangle t;
    t.setdata();
    float s=(float)(t.a+t.b+t.c)/2; 
    float area=sqrt(s*(s-t.a)*(s-t.b)*(s-t.c));
    cout<<"Area="<<area<<endl;
	cout<<"Perimeter="<<s*2;
    return 0;
}
///3////////////////////////////////////
#include<iostream>
using namespace std;
void selectionSort(int a[], int n){
	int i, j, min, temp;
	for(i = 0; i < n - 1; i++){
      min = i;
      for (j = i + 1; j < n; j++)
      if (a[j] < a[min])
      min = j;
      temp = a[i];
      a[i] = a[min];
      a[min] = temp;
   }
}
int main(){
	int n,a[100];
	cout<<"enter the size of array"<<endl;
   	cin>>n;
	cout<<"enter array:"<<endl;
	for (int i = 0; i < n; i++){
		cin>>a[i];
	}
	cout<<endl;
	selectionSort(a, n);
	cout<<"sorted array is "<<endl;
	for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
	cout<< a[i] <<" ";
	return 0;
}
//4////////////////////
#include<iostream>
using namespace std;
int main(){
	int n,a[100],num;
	cout<<"enter the size of array"<<endl;
   	cin>>n;
	cout<<"enter array:"<<endl;
	for (int i = 0; i < n; i++){
		cin>>a[i];
	}
	cout<<endl;
	cout<<"enter the element to search"<<endl;
	cin>>num;
	for (int i = 0; i < n; i++){
		if(a[i]==num){
			cout<<"element found at "<<i+1;
		}
	}
	return 0;
}

21/10/22, 20:29 - Abhishek Joshi: #include <iostream>
#include <stack>
using namespace std;

int precedence(char c)
{
    if (c == '^')
        return 3;
    else if (c == '/' || c == '*')
        return 2;
    else if (c == '+' || c == '-')
        return 1;
    else
        return -1;
}

string infix_to_postfix(string str){
    stack<char>st;
    string res;

    for(int i=0;i<str.length();i++){
        if((str[i]>='a' && str[i]<='z') ||(str[i]>='A' && str[i]<='Z')){
            res += str[i];
        }
        else if(str[i]=='('){
            st.push(str[i]);
        }
        else if(str[i]==')'){
            while(!st.empty() && st.top()=='('){
                res+=st.top();
                st.pop();
            }
            if(!st.empty()){
                st.pop();
            }
        }
        else{
            while (!st.empty() && precedence(st.top())>=precedence(str[i])){
                res+=st.top();
                st.pop();
            }
            st.push(str[i]);
        }
        
        
    }
    while(!st.empty()){
            res+=st.top();
            st.pop();
        }
    return res;
}


int main(){
    cout<<"Enter a expression : ";
    string s;
    cin>>s;
    cout<<endl;
    cout<<"postfix : "<<infix_to_postfix(s);

return 0;
}

09/12/22, 11:30 - àº¸Ansul Rawat: Ques23.WAP to understand multiple inheritance
Ques24.Create a student class with data members(roll_no(protected)) , member
functions(get_no(),put_no()).then derive a class test from student with data
members(sub1,sub2) and member functions
(get_marks(float,float),put_marks()).then derive a class result from test with
data members(total) and member functions(display). finally display the
information of the student.
Ques25. Create a student class with data members(roll_no(protected)) ,
member functions(get_no(),put_no()).then derive a class test from student with
data members(sub1,sub2) and member functions
(get_marks(float,float),put_marks()).create another class sports with data
mambers score and member functions(get_score(),put_score()).then derive a
class result from test and sports with data members(total) and member
functions(display). finally display the information of the student.
Q26.WAP in c++ to add two numbers using single inheritance accept those two
numbers from the user , in base class and display the sum of these numbers in
derived class.

Ques27.Create a student class with data members(roll_no(protected)) , member
functions(get_no(),put_no()).then derive a class test from student with data
members(sub1,sub2) and member functions
(get_marks(float,float),put_marks()).then derive a class result from test with

18/01/23, 07:49 - àº¸Ansul Rawat: Share market, also known as stock market, is a platform where publicly traded companies' stocks are bought and sold. It is a place where investors can buy shares of a company with the hope of earning a profit when the value of those shares increases. The share market is a barometer of the overall economy, and it is considered as a leading indicator of economic growth. The prices of shares in the stock market are affected by various internal and external factors such as company performance, economic conditions, interest rates, and political developments.

Investing in the stock market can be a great way to grow your wealth over time, but it's also important to remember that it comes with risks. It's crucial for investors to do their research and understand the companies and industries they are investing in, as well as being aware of the current market conditions before making any investment decisions. Diversifying your portfolio by investing in different sectors and companies can also help mitigate risk.

In recent times, the share market has been highly volatile due to the COVID-19 pandemic and its economic impact. Many companies have seen their stock prices drop, while others have seen gains. However, despite the uncertainty and volatility, the share market continues to be an important tool for investors to grow their wealth over time.

It's important to note that investing in the stock market should be a long-term strategy and not a get-rich-quick scheme. It's always recommended to consult with a financial advisor before making any investment decisions

23/02/23, 15:02 - +91 70601 30985: Dear Students,

We are thrilled to announce the launch of the ACM Student Chapter at Graphic Era Hill University, a community that brings together computer science students from all disciplines to learn, connect, and grow together.

ACM (Association for Computing Machinery) is the world's largest educational and scientific computing society, uniting computing professionals and students from around the globe. The organization has been at the forefront of computing advancements for over 75 years, fostering innovation, promoting excellence in research and education, and advancing computing as a science and a profession.

Joining the ACM Student Chapter at Graphic Era Hill University comes with many perks and benefits, including:

â€¢Networking Opportunities: ACM Student Chapter members get access to a vast network of computing professionals, including industry experts, researchers, and fellow students.
â€¢Skill Development: ACM Student Chapters organize a variety of events, workshops, and hackathons aimed at developing technical skills, career skills, and leadership skills.
â€¢Exposure: Members of the ACM Student Chapter will have opportunities to participate in national and international conferences, presenting their work, networking with others, and staying up-to-date on the latest trends in computing.
â€¢Awards and Recognition: ACM offers various awards and competitions to recognize outstanding research and achievements in the field of computing. As a member of the ACM Student Chapter, you will have the opportunity to participate in these competitions and be recognized for your work.
â€¢Get to learn about Industry-Hot topics and technologies with practical applications and implementations on weekends.
â€¢Seek the guidance of professionals on conducting research and writing research papers & patents.
Joining the ACM Student Chapter is an excellent way to develop your skills, gain exposure, and connect with others in the field of computing. We look forward to welcoming you to this vibrant and engaging community.

You can apply using give form attached below:
https://forms.gle/GsntDDvy4LNZ58cr8
Sincerely,
Madhvan Bajaj
Treasurer
GEHU ACM Student Chapter

03/03/23, 08:29 - àº¸Ansul Rawat: import java.util.Scanner;

public class Rectangle {
    private int length;
    private int width;

    public Rectangle(int length, int width) {
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }

    public int getArea() {
        return length * width;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter the length of the rectangle: ");
        int length = input.nextInt();

        System.out.print("Enter the width of the rectangle: ");
        int width = input.nextInt();

        Rectangle rectangle = new Rectangle(length, width);
        int area = rectangle.getArea();

        System.out.println("The area of the rectangle is " + area);
    }
}

13/05/23, 07:52 - àº¸Ansul Rawat: All students have been mailed their E-Passes for Campus Entry for the Celebrity Nights under GRAFEST 2023.

The pass is valid for single entry and will be scanned at GATE No. 2 for all 3 Days. 

The link will automatically have your updated pass for Day 1, Day 2 and Day 3 of GRAFEST 2023.

Here are important points that you need to be aware of before planning your visit to GRAFEST

1. ENTRY for students into GRAFEST 2023 will be only through GATE No. 2

2. All students are required to carry their University Identity Cards to enter the premises of the University. No student will be allowed into the campus without valid University Identity Cards.

3. The Grafest E-Pass made available to you in the above link is a mandatory item for all students to be able to attend the Celebrity Night.
 
4. The pass will be scanned at the Entry Point for the Fest and will be a one-way ticket. Once inside the venue, students are advised not to leave, as anyone who leaves will be denied re-entry.

5. One pass will allow only a single person entry. Please do not share your pass with anyone, as this would mean you will not be able to attend the fest.

6. We advise you to secure your entry into the campus latest by 6 PM on each day, so as to avoid any kind of inconvenience due to last minute rush.

7. In case any of your classmates/friends studying at Graphic Era havenâ€™t received their passes due to their Email IDs not being updated, they can immediately reach out to their department faculties and get their E-Mail Updated. Pass Issuing will be closed by 3:00 PM today.
 
SECURITY / BEHAVIOURAL INSTRUCTIONS:

1. No bags (College Bags, Sling Bags, Backpacks etc.) will be permitted inside the campus for the celebrity night. For female students, small handbags, clutches will be allowed. No additional bags will be allowed. Please note and make your arrangements accordingly.

2. The campus entry will be videographer and will be equipped with Breathalyzers and Alcometers - Any student found to be under the influence of Alcohol or any other intoxicant will be denied entry into the campus and will also face disciplinary action. Your security is of paramount importance and we expect you to follow this instruction with utmost sincerity and enjoy the fest responsibly.

3. Any individual found even as much as trying to imposter as a Graphic Era Student trying to enter the campus without permission will be dealt with seriously - Heavy Police Personnel Deployment at the campus will ensure the same.

4. BUSES will operate for the convenience of the students while also ensuring safe departure of the students. Students are advised to ensure their timings, whereabouts are informed to their parents and local guardians.

5. Speedy Driving, Triple Riding, Riding without Helmets, Driving under the influence of an intoxicant, hooliganism of any kind by any individual will be dealt very severely by Uttarakhand Police who are a part of the arrangements of GRAFEST at all times this year.

All of the aforementioned points are meant to ensure that all Graphics are able to enjoy the most awaited cultural fest of the year with utmost ease, with utmost safety and reach their homes safe and sound after the events. In case of any emergencies, requests, issues, the organising team at the venue can be reached out to.

The campus will be equipped with Medical Facilities and EMTs for handling any kind of medical emergencies.

Hope to see you there on time today, tomorrow and day after!

Cheers,
Team Grafest

30/09/23, 08:25 - àº¸Ansul Rawat: Anand P A:
This information is pertaining to Quant.

Following is the flow of sub topics in Number System:

1. Understanding and comparison of Prime and Composite Numbers.

2. Properties of Remainders.

3. Divisibility rules of numbers.

4. All aspects related to Factors (number of factors, sum of factors, odd and even factors, factors that are coprime etc)

5. LCM, HCF and applications.

6. Types of LCM problems.

7. Applications of HCF

8. Concept of the last digit.

9. Alphanumerals.

Mid Term Exam will have two topics in Quant : 
Number System and Percentage.

23/10/23, 10:43 - +91 70601 30985: #include <stdio.h>

// Function to calculate the coefficient of Y
double p_cal(double p, int n) {
    double temp = 1;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
        temp *= (p - i + 1);
    }
    return temp;
}

// Function to calculate factorial
int fact(int n) {
    int f = 1;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; ++i) {
        f *= i;
    }
    return f;
}

int main() {
    int n = 7; // Number of data points
    double x[] = {1, 1.05, 1.10, 1.15, 1.20, 1.25, 1.30}; // X values
    double y[] = {2.7183, 2.8577, 3.0042, 3.1582, 3.3201, 3.4903, 3.6693}; // Corresponding Y values
    double value = 1.17; // Value at which interpolation is to be done
    double h = x[1] - x[0]; // Step size

    // Calculating forward difference table
    double forwardDiff[n][n];
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        forwardDiff[i][0] = y[i];
    }
    for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n - i; ++j) {
            forwardDiff[j][i] = forwardDiff[j + 1][i - 1] - forwardDiff[j][i - 1];
        }
    }

    // Calculating p-value
    double p = (value - x[0]) / h;

    // Calculating interpolated value using Gauss's Forward Interpolation Formula
    double sum = forwardDiff[0][0];
    for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
        sum += (p_cal(p, i) * forwardDiff[0][i]) / fact(i);
    }

    // Output the interpolated value
    printf("Interpolated value at %.2f is %.4f\n", value, sum);

    return 0;
}
